{[%evp 13,78,60,55,51,49,46,43,48,61,46,46,47,54,19,20,19,27,-16,-12,-11,0,-11,0,-1,0,-35,9,-66,-57,-166,-142,-144,-114,-215,-199,-211,-203,-204,-157,-164,-126,-123,-107,-246,-123,-294,-258,-277,-262,-280,-206,-237,-190,-397,-373,-346,-314,-739,-403,-419,-575,-562,-578,-562,-559,-518,-380] C84: Closed Ruy Lopez: Unusual White 6th moves IM / WGM Padmini Rout, ChessBase: 'Anna Muzychuk has unfortunately had quite a bad tournament performance, but with a pairing against the newcomer Vaishali Rameshbabu may have been an opportunity for the veteran to get a win. With white, Muzychuk opted for 1. e4 going into a well-known Open Ruy Lopez line. However, as soon as getting out of the (well-travelled) opening line chosen, Muzychuk made a few inaccuracies that gave Vaishali the leverage to get into the position. Playing perfectly, Vaishali gradually built up her advantage until it was completely crushing — the engine giving several forced mating lines before Muzychuk resigned — giving the newcomer, Vaishali, another win. ______ An interesting game where White gives an exchange for only a pawn and a Bishop, counting on dominance on the dark squares. It would work but Black has come prepared and blitzes out the opening actually taking White by surprise. _______'} 1. e4 {[%emt 0:00:01]} e5 {[%emt 0:03:21]} 2. Nf3 {[%emt 0:00:01]} Nc6 {[%emt 0:00:00]} 3. Bb5 {[%emt 0:00:01]} a6 {[%emt 0:00:02]} 4. Ba4 {[%emt 0:00:01]} Nf6 {[%emt 0:00:01]} 5. O-O {[%emt 0:00:02]} Nxe4 {[%emt 0:00:01]} 6. d4 {[%emt 0:00:01]} Be7 {[%emt 0:00:02]} 7. Re1 {[%emt 0:00:12][%cal Bf1e1,Be1e4,Be4e5][%mdl 32]} b5 {[%emt 0:00:01]} 8. Rxe4 {[%emt 0:00:03] [#] Hoping for Bb3.} (8. Nxe5 Nxe5 9. Rxe4 Ng6 $11) (8. dxe5 Nxf2 9. Kxf2 bxa4 $17) 8... d5 $1 {[%emt 0:00:01]} 9. Nxe5 {[%emt 0:00:01]} Nxe5 {[%emt 0:00:01]} 10. Rxe5 {[%emt 0:00:02] White is slightly better.} bxa4 {[%emt 0:00:00]} 11. Qe2 {[%emt 0:00:03] White is more active.} Be6 {[%emt 0:00:02]} 12. f4 $1 {[%emt 0:00:05]} Kf8 {[%emt 0:00:02]} 13. Nc3 {[%